const fs = require('fs');
const path = require('path');

const outDir = path.join(__dirname, 'en', 'blog');
if (!fs.existsSync(outDir)) fs.mkdirSync(outDir, { recursive: true });

const translations = [
  {
    file: 'freelancer-inkubator-czy-firma.html',
    title: 'Freelancer in 2026 — Business Incubator or Your Own Company?',
    desc: 'Comparison of freelancer career paths: unregistered activity, business incubator, or sole proprietorship (JDG)? Which model to choose in 2026?',
    badge: 'Incubator', badgeColor: '#7c5cbf',
    author: 'FDK Team &middot; 16.01.2026',
    toc: [
      ['#trzy-modele', 'Three freelancer work models'],
      ['#nierejestrowana', 'Unregistered activity'],
      ['#inkubator', 'Business incubator'],
      ['#jdg', 'Your own company (JDG)'],
      ['#ktory-model', 'Which model to choose?']
    ],
    sections: [
      ['trzy-modele', 'Three freelancer work models', `<p>The freelancer market in Poland is growing dynamically — according to the latest research, 67.9% of people working in the freelance model are under 35 years old. This is a generation that values flexibility, remote work, and independence from a single employer. At the same time, they face a key question: in what legal form should they run their business?</p><p>In 2026, a freelancer in Poland has three basic models to choose from: unregistered activity (for small revenues), a business incubator (for those who don't want to start their own company), and a sole proprietorship (JDG). Each of these models has its advantages and limitations, and the choice depends on the scale of activity, type of clients, and individual preferences.</p><p>It is worth emphasizing that there is no single universal solution. A programmer earning PLN 15,000 per month on B2B contracts will have different needs than a graphic designer doing occasional jobs for PLN 2,000. The key is understanding the costs, obligations, and possibilities of each model.</p>`],
      ['nierejestrowana', 'Unregistered activity', `<p>Unregistered activity is the simplest form of earning, intended for people with small revenues. In 2026, the monthly limit is 75% of the minimum wage, which at a minimum wage of PLN 4,666 gross gives approximately PLN 3,500 per month. Exceeding this limit in any month means an obligation to register a business.</p><p>The advantage of unregistered activity is no obligation to pay ZUS contributions, no need for full accounting, and no registration in CEIDG. It is enough to keep simplified sales records and settle income in the annual PIT-36 return according to the tax scale (12% up to PLN 120,000, 32% above).</p><p>The limitation is not only the revenue limit but also the inability to issue VAT invoices (which excludes cooperation with many companies) and the lack of a NIP number as an entrepreneur. Unregistered activity works only as a temporary solution or a supplement to employment with small orders.</p>`],
      ['inkubator', 'Business incubator', `<p>A business incubator is a solution that combines the advantages of running a business with the lack of formalities typical of your own company. The freelancer operates within the incubator entity, which issues invoices on their behalf, handles accounting, and settles taxes. The cost of using an incubator is approximately PLN 400 per month, covering full administrative support.</p><p>A key advantage of the incubator is no obligation to pay ZUS contributions (the freelancer is registered for insurance by the incubator on employment or contract terms). Additionally, within the incubator, it is possible to use preferential taxation — the flat-rate tax can be as low as 6% depending on the type of activity. The incubator also provides a registration address, which is important for people working from home.</p><p>The incubator is particularly attractive for people starting their freelancing adventure, foreigners (who may not have the right to register a JDG), and for specialists who don't want to deal with formalities. The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation offers full incubator services with the ability to launch business within 15 minutes.</p>`],
      ['jdg', 'Your own company (JDG)', `<p>A sole proprietorship (JDG) is the classic form of running a business in Poland. Registration is free and done through the CEIDG portal. However, from the moment of registration, the entrepreneur becomes a ZUS contribution payer, which in 2026 means a cost of approximately PLN 1,600 per month (full ZUS) or approximately PLN 600 (Small ZUS Plus, if the discount applies).</p><p>JDG gives full freedom in running a business — the entrepreneur decides on the form of taxation (scale, 19% flat rate, lump sum), can deduct business costs, issue VAT invoices, and freely cooperate with domestic and foreign clients. From 2026, use of the National e-Invoice System (KSeF) becomes mandatory.</p><p>The disadvantage of JDG is the fixed ZUS cost regardless of revenue, the need for accounting (independently or through an accounting office for an additional fee), and full personal liability for business obligations. For freelancers with stable, high revenues (above PLN 8,000-10,000 per month), JDG is usually more profitable than an incubator.</p>`],
      ['ktory-model', 'Which model to choose?', `<p>The choice of model depends primarily on the level of revenue and stability of orders. If your monthly revenue does not exceed PLN 3,500 and you don't need VAT invoices, unregistered activity will be sufficient. It's a good starting point, allowing you to test the market without obligations.</p><p>A business incubator works well when your revenue is between PLN 3,000 and 10,000 per month, you need to issue invoices, but you don't want to pay ZUS and deal with accounting. It is also the only option for foreigners who cannot register a JDG. At a cost of approximately PLN 400 per month, the incubator offers comprehensive service and minimal formalities.</p><p>Your own company (JDG) becomes profitable with stable revenues above PLN 8,000-10,000 per month. Higher fixed costs (ZUS + accounting) are compensated by greater flexibility and tax optimization possibilities. Remember, however, that transitioning from an incubator to JDG is simple and can be done at any time — you don't have to make this decision right away.</p>`]
    ]
  },
  {
    file: 'niebieska-karta-ue.html',
    title: 'EU Blue Card After June 1, 2025 — New Mobility Rules',
    desc: 'EU Blue Card reform — new mobility rules for highly qualified foreigners, conditions for obtaining one, and benefits after June 1, 2025.',
    badge: 'Foreigners', badgeColor: '#00BBFF',
    author: 'FDK Team &middot; 14.01.2026',
    toc: [
      ['#co-to', 'What is the EU Blue Card?'],
      ['#zmiany', 'Key changes from June 1, 2025'],
      ['#kto-moze', 'Who can apply for the Blue Card?'],
      ['#procedura', 'Application procedure'],
      ['#mobilnosc', 'New EU mobility rules'],
      ['#korzysci', 'Benefits for employees and employers']
    ],
    sections: [
      ['co-to', 'What is the EU Blue Card?', `<p>The EU Blue Card is a residence and work permit intended for highly qualified workers from outside the European Union. It was introduced by an EU directive to attract talent to member states and is the European equivalent of the American Green Card, though with different awarding rules.</p><p>In Poland, the Blue Card is issued as a temporary residence permit for the purpose of performing work requiring high qualifications. The card holder receives a residence card with the annotation "EU Blue Card," which entitles them to legal residence and work in Poland and — after meeting conditions — to mobility within the entire European Union.</p><p>Until now, the Blue Card has not been very popular in Poland due to restrictive conditions and limited mobility. The reform that came into force on June 1, 2025, aims to change this, making the instrument more attractive for both employees and employers.</p>`],
      ['zmiany', 'Key changes from June 1, 2025', `<p>The most important change is the expansion of the definition of "high qualifications." Previously, a diploma from higher education lasting at least 3 years was required. The new regulations also allow people with at least 3 years of documented professional experience in a position requiring comparable skills, even without formal higher education.</p><p>The salary threshold required to obtain a Blue Card has also been lowered. Previously, the salary had to be at least 150% of the average wage in the country. The new threshold is 100-140% of the average wage (depending on the sector), which in Poland in 2026 means approximately PLN 8,000 to PLN 11,200 gross per month.</p><p>Facilitations have also been introduced for people with international protection beneficiary status — they can apply for a Blue Card without losing their existing protection status. This is an important change that opens a career path for refugees with high qualifications.</p>`],
      ['kto-moze', 'Who can apply for the Blue Card?', `<p>A third-country national (from outside the EU/EEA/Switzerland) who simultaneously meets the following conditions may apply for the EU Blue Card: possesses higher professional qualifications (higher education diploma or at least 3 years of professional experience in the field), has an employment contract or binding job offer for at least 6 months, and earns a salary at the required level.</p><p>The new regulations expand the range of qualifying professions. In addition to traditional sectors such as IT, engineering, medicine, and finance, the Blue Card is now also available for specialists in artificial intelligence, cybersecurity, green technologies, and project management. The list of deficit sectors with lower salary thresholds is updated annually.</p><p>It is worth noting that the Blue Card is not available for self-employed persons — it is an instrument intended exclusively for hired employees. Foreigners planning to run a business in Poland should consider other forms of residence legalization, such as a residence permit for the purpose of conducting business activity.</p>`],
      ['procedura', 'Application procedure', `<p>The EU Blue Card application is submitted to the voivode competent for the foreigner's place of residence (or intended place of residence for people staying abroad). From 2026, the application can be submitted electronically through the MOS system or in person at the voivodeship office.</p><p>The application should be accompanied by: a completed application form, a current biometric photo, a copy of the passport, documents confirming qualifications (diploma or certificate of professional experience), an employment contract or job offer with a specified salary, health insurance, and confirmation of having a place of residence.</p><p>The application processing time is up to 90 days from the date of submitting a complete application. In practice, thanks to the MOS system, complete applications without reservations are processed within 30-60 days. The Blue Card is issued for the period of the employment contract plus 3 months, but not longer than 4 years.</p>`],
      ['mobilnosc', 'New EU mobility rules', `<p>The biggest revolution in the Blue Card reform are the new intra-EU mobility rules. Previously, a Blue Card holder could move to another EU country only after 18 months of legal residence in the first member state. The new regulations shorten this period to 12 months.</p><p>Moreover, the possibility of short-term business mobility without the need to obtain additional permits has been introduced. A Blue Card holder issued in Poland can stay and work in another EU state for up to 90 days within 180 days for business purposes — client meetings, training, industry conferences.</p><p>For long-term mobility (over 90 days), it is still necessary to submit a Blue Card application in the destination country, but the procedure is significantly simplified. The new country must process the application within 30 days, and the card holder can start working from the day of application submission, without waiting for the decision.</p>`],
      ['korzysci', 'Benefits for employees and employers', `<p>For employees, the key benefit is the path to permanent residence — after 5 years of legal residence on the Blue Card (of which at least 2 years in the last country), the holder can apply for EU long-term resident status with the annotation "former EU Blue Card holder," which gives additional mobility rights.</p><p>The new regulations also allow easier family reunification. Family members of the Blue Card holder (spouse and minor children) can apply for a residence permit in a simplified procedure, with the right to work without additional permits. The family application can be submitted simultaneously with the main application.</p><p>Employers, on the other hand, gain access to a broader pool of qualified candidates from around the world. The recruitment procedure with the Blue Card is simpler than a standard work permit — it does not require a labor market test (checking whether there are candidates from the EU for the position). This significantly speeds up the process of hiring specialists from abroad.</p>`]
    ]
  },
  {
    file: 'firma-w-polsce-cudzoziemiec.html',
    title: 'How to Start a Business in Poland as a Non-EU Foreigner in 2026?',
    desc: 'Guide to the business registration procedure in Poland for non-EU foreigners — documents, legal forms, and alternatives.',
    badge: 'Guide', badgeColor: '#3498db',
    author: 'FDK Team &middot; 08.01.2026',
    toc: [
      ['#kto-moze', 'Who can start a business in Poland?'],
      ['#formy-prawne', 'Available legal forms'],
      ['#jdg-procedura', 'JDG registration step by step'],
      ['#spolka', 'Establishing a limited liability company'],
      ['#inkubator', 'Incubator as an alternative'],
      ['#dokumenty', 'Required documents']
    ],
    sections: [
      ['kto-moze', 'Who can start a business in Poland?', `<p>The right to register a sole proprietorship (JDG) in Poland is granted to non-EU foreigners provided they have an appropriate residence title. This entitlement applies to people with: a permanent residence permit, an EU long-term resident permit, a temporary residence permit granted for family reunification, refugee status, subsidiary protection, consent for tolerated stay, or temporary protection.</p><p>People with a temporary residence and work permit (the most common type of permit) generally cannot register a JDG — unless they have an additional residence permit for conducting business activity. This restriction is one of the biggest barriers for foreigners wanting to start their own business in Poland.</p><p>An exception are citizens of countries with which Poland has signed reciprocity agreements (e.g., USA, South Korea). Citizens of these countries can establish a JDG on the same terms as Poles, regardless of the type of residence permit held. The list of such countries is, however, limited.</p>`],
      ['formy-prawne', 'Available legal forms', `<p>Foreigners who cannot register a JDG have other forms of conducting business at their disposal. The most commonly chosen option is a limited liability company (sp. z o.o.), which can be established by any foreigner without restrictions regarding residence title. A limited liability company provides personal asset protection and builds a professional image.</p><p>Other available forms include: limited partnership, general partnership, joint-stock company, and simple joint-stock company (PSA). Each has different capital requirements and liability rules. The simple joint-stock company, introduced in 2021, requires only PLN 1 of share capital and is particularly attractive for startups.</p><p>The choice of legal form should take into account the scale of planned activity, number of partners, tax needs, and service costs. A limited liability company requires minimum capital of PLN 5,000 and full accounting, which generates higher costs than JDG but offers greater development opportunities.</p>`],
      ['jdg-procedura', 'JDG registration step by step', `<p>Foreigners entitled to register a JDG do so free of charge through the CEIDG (Central Register and Information on Economic Activity) portal. The CEIDG-1 form can be filled in online at ceidg.gov.pl and submitted using a trusted profile or qualified signature. Alternatively, the form can be submitted in person at any commune office.</p><p>The CEIDG-1 form requires: personal data, residential and business addresses, company name (must include first and last name), PKD codes defining the type of activity, chosen form of taxation, and method of keeping accounts. The form also serves as registration with ZUS and the tax office.</p><p>From the moment of CEIDG entry, the entrepreneur can start operating. Registration usually takes 1 business day. However, it is worth opening a business bank account beforehand, as the account number is needed for settlements with ZUS and the tax office. Some banks require additional documents from foreigners (e.g., sworn translation of passport).</p>`],
      ['spolka', 'Establishing a limited liability company', `<p>A limited liability company can be established in two ways: traditionally through a notary or electronically through the S24 portal (IT system of the Ministry of Justice). Registration through S24 is faster (KRS entry within 1 business day) and cheaper (PLN 350 in court fees instead of PLN 600 plus notary costs).</p><p>To register a company through S24, a trusted profile or qualified electronic signature is needed. A foreigner without a PESEL number must obtain one before registration — the PESEL application is submitted at the commune office. The share capital (minimum PLN 5,000) must be paid to the company's account within 7 days of registration.</p><p>After KRS registration, the company must complete additional formalities: registration with the tax office (NIP-8), registration as a contribution payer with ZUS, opening a bank account, and — for VAT-paying companies — registration on the VAT-R form. The entire process from start to finish usually takes 2-3 weeks.</p>`],
      ['inkubator', 'Incubator as an alternative', `<p>For foreigners who do not have the right to register a JDG or do not want to bear the costs of establishing a company, a business incubator is an ideal alternative. An incubator allows you to legally conduct earning activity, issue invoices, and accept orders without registering your own company.</p><p>In the incubator model, the foreigner enters into an agreement with the incubator, which becomes the formal entity issuing invoices and settling taxes. The freelancer maintains full independence in acquiring clients and completing orders, while the incubator handles the entire administrative side. The cost is approximately PLN 400 per month, which is many times less than running a limited liability company.</p><p>The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation specializes in incubator services for foreigners. We offer support in Polish, English, Ukrainian, and Russian. Launching business within the incubator takes only 15 minutes and does not require a PESEL number, trusted profile, or office visit. It is the fastest and simplest path to legal earning in Poland.</p>`],
      ['dokumenty', 'Required documents', `<p>Regardless of the chosen form of business, a foreigner needs the following documents: a valid passport (or other travel document), a residence card or other document confirming legal residence, a PESEL number (for JDG registration and company registration through S24), and an address of residence in Poland.</p><p>For notarial company registration, a sworn translation of the passport into Polish is required. The notary may also request a document confirming the address of residence (e.g., a rental agreement). For JDG registration, a sworn translation is not required but recommended for office visits.</p><p>Foreigners using a business incubator need only: a passport (scan or photo), a document confirming legal residence in Poland (residence card, visa, stamp in passport), and a bank account number for salary payment. The incubator does not require a PESEL number or trusted profile, which significantly simplifies the entire process.</p>`]
    ]
  }
];

