// Now generate shorter stub translations for the remaining 14 files
const remaining = [
  { file: 'nowy-wzor-wniosku-pobyt-czasowy.html', title: 'New Temporary Residence Application Form Since December 2025 — What Changed?', desc: 'Changes in the temporary residence permit application form from December 2025 — new fields, requirements, and how to correctly fill out the application.', badge: 'Foreigners', badgeColor: '#00BBFF', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 05.01.2026', toc: [['#podstawa-prawna','Legal basis for changes'],['#co-sie-zmienilo','What changed in the form?'],['#nowe-pola','New fields and sections'],['#jak-wypelnic','How to correctly fill out the new application'],['#najczestsze-bledy','Most common mistakes'],['#gdzie-pobrac','Where to download the new form']], content: `<h2 id="podstawa-prawna" class="fw-bold mb-3">Legal basis for changes</h2><p>The new template for the temporary residence permit application was introduced by a regulation of the Minister of Internal Affairs and Administration dated November 28, 2025. The regulation came into force on December 15, 2025, meaning that from this date all applications must be submitted on the new form. Applications submitted on the old form after this date will be returned with a request for resubmission.</p><p>The form change is part of a broader reform of the foreigner service system in Poland, related to the implementation of the MOS system and adaptation to new EU directives. The new form was designed for electronic data processing, which is expected to speed up case handling.</p><h2 id="co-sie-zmienilo" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">What changed in the form?</h2><p>The most important change is the simplification of the application structure. The previous form was 8 pages and contained many repetitive fields. The new form has been shortened to 6 pages, and duplicated fields have been eliminated. At the same time, new sections related to digital identification of the applicant have been added.</p><p>The graphic layout of the form has changed — the new template is clearer, with clearly separated sections and filling instructions placed directly next to the relevant fields. Mandatory fields are marked with an asterisk, making it easier to identify information that must be filled in.</p><h2 id="nowe-pola" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">New fields and sections</h2><p>The new form includes a section for electronic correspondence address. The foreigner provides an email address to which notifications about changes in case status will be sent. This is a mandatory field and replaces the previous mail-only communication, significantly speeding up correspondence with the office.</p><p>A mobile phone number field with country code has also been added, enabling SMS contact in urgent matters. A new "Additional information" section allows the applicant to describe special circumstances that may affect the case — e.g., pregnancy, illness, documented family ties in Poland.</p><h2 id="jak-wypelnic" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to correctly fill out the new application</h2><p>The application should be filled in with block letters, using a black or blue pen. For electronic completion (fillable PDF form), use a font size of at least 10 points. All text fields are filled in Polish, except for first and last names, which are given according to the travel document.</p><p>The section regarding the purpose of stay requires special attention. Mark the appropriate purpose (work, studies, family reunification, business activity, etc.) and provide detailed justification in the description field. Generic phrases like "I want to work in Poland" may result in a request for supplementation, extending the proceedings.</p><h2 id="najczestsze-bledy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Most common mistakes</h2><p>The most common mistake is using the old application form. Since December 15, 2025, voivodeship offices accept only applications on the new form. Before submitting, check that the form has the current regulation date in the footer. Old forms are unfortunately still available on many websites.</p><p>Another common mistake is incomplete filling of the section on previous stays in the Schengen area. The new form requires detailed information about all stays in the last 5 years, including entry and exit dates, basis of stay, and country of stay.</p><h2 id="gdzie-pobrac" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Where to download the new form</h2><p>The official new application form is available on the Office for Foreigners website (udsc.gov.pl) under the "Application forms" tab. The form can be downloaded in PDF format for printing or in an interactive version for computer completion. We recommend using official sources only to avoid the risk of downloading an outdated or modified form.</p><p>The form is also available in the MOS system after logging into the user account. When submitting an application electronically through MOS, the form is generated automatically based on data entered into the system — there is no need to download or fill it in separately.</p>` },
  { file: 'maly-zus-plus-2026.html', title: 'How Are Small ZUS Plus Rules Changing in 2026?', desc: 'New Small ZUS Plus rules in 2026 — who qualifies, how to calculate contributions, changes in qualifying periods, and revenue limits.', badge: 'ZUS', badgeColor: '#2ecc71', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 29.12.2025', toc: [['#czym-jest','What is Small ZUS Plus?'],['#kto-kwalifikuje','Who qualifies in 2026?'],['#zmiany-okresow','Changes in qualifying periods'],['#kalkulacja','How to calculate contributions?'],['#zgloszenie','Deadline and method of registration'],['#alternatywy','Alternatives to Small ZUS Plus']], content: `<h2 id="czym-jest" class="fw-bold mb-3">What is Small ZUS Plus?</h2><p>Small ZUS Plus is a social insurance contribution relief intended for entrepreneurs running a sole proprietorship with low revenues. Under this relief, the contribution base is calculated proportionally to income from the previous calendar year, instead of the standard base of 60% of average wages.</p><p>The relief was introduced in 2020 as an extension of the earlier "Small ZUS" and has since been one of the most important tools supporting small entrepreneurs. Thanks to Small ZUS Plus, a low-income entrepreneur can pay significantly lower ZUS contributions — in some cases even 60-70% less.</p><h2 id="kto-kwalifikuje" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Who qualifies in 2026?</h2><p>Small ZUS Plus is available to entrepreneurs who in the previous calendar year (2025) ran a business for at least 60 days and achieved revenue not exceeding PLN 120,000. The revenue limit is fixed and not indexed, meaning that with rising inflation, more entrepreneurs may exceed it.</p><p>Those who cannot use this relief include: entrepreneurs settling on a tax card, those conducting business for a former employer (if in the current or previous year they performed the same activities as under employment), entrepreneurs subject to social insurance from another title, and companies.</p><h2 id="zmiany-okresow" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Changes in qualifying periods</h2><p>The most important change in 2026 is the modification of the relief period calculation rules. Previously, Small ZUS Plus was available for a maximum of 36 months within 60 consecutive months of business activity. From 2026, this changes to 48 months within 72 months — meaning the entrepreneur can use the relief for 4 years, then must pay full ZUS for at least 2 years.</p><h2 id="kalkulacja" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to calculate contributions?</h2><p>The contribution base under Small ZUS Plus is calculated using the formula: (annual income from previous year / number of days of business activity) x 30. The calculated base cannot be lower than 30% of the minimum wage (in 2026: PLN 1,399.80) and not higher than 60% of average wages.</p><p>Standard percentage rates are applied to the calculated base: pension 19.52%, disability 8%, sickness 2.45% (voluntary), accident 1.67%. The total social contribution rate is 31.64% (without sickness) or 34.09% (with sickness).</p><h2 id="zgloszenie" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Deadline and method of registration</h2><p>Registration for Small ZUS Plus must be done by January 31 of the year in which the entrepreneur wants to use the relief. For entrepreneurs resuming or starting activity after January 1, the deadline is 7 days from the date of starting. Missing the deadline means losing the right to the relief for that year.</p><h2 id="alternatywy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Alternatives to Small ZUS Plus</h2><p>Entrepreneurs who do not qualify for Small ZUS Plus or have exhausted the relief period can consider several alternatives. The first is a business incubator — in this model, the entrepreneur does not pay ZUS on business activity, and contributions are paid by the incubator. The incubator cost (approx. PLN 400/month) is usually lower than full ZUS.</p><p>The second option is the startup relief (ZUS Startup), which is available to new entrepreneurs for the first 6 months. The third alternative is running a business as a limited liability company, where a partner is not subject to mandatory social insurance (provided the company has at least two partners).</p>` },
  { file: 'forma-opodatkowania-2026.html', title: 'Is It Worth Changing Your Tax Form in 2026?', desc: 'Analysis of taxation forms in 2026 — lump sum, tax scale, or flat tax? When is it worth changing and what are the deadlines.', badge: 'Taxes', badgeColor: '#2ecc71', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 17.12.2025', toc: [['#formy','Available taxation forms'],['#skala','Tax scale (progressive PIT)'],['#liniowy','Flat tax 19%'],['#ryczalt','Lump-sum tax on recorded revenues'],['#porownanie','Comparison — when does what pay off'],['#terminy','Deadlines for changing tax form']], content: `<h2 id="formy" class="fw-bold mb-3">Available taxation forms</h2><p>Entrepreneurs running a sole proprietorship in Poland have three main taxation forms to choose from: the tax scale (progressive taxation), flat tax at 19%, and lump-sum tax on recorded revenues. Each of these forms has different rates, different rules for accounting costs, and different consequences for health insurance contributions.</p><p>The choice of taxation form is one of the most important financial decisions for an entrepreneur, as it directly affects the amount of income tax and health contribution. An incorrect choice can cost several thousand PLN per year.</p><h2 id="skala" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Tax scale (progressive PIT)</h2><p>The tax scale is the default form of taxation. In 2026, two thresholds apply: 12% on income up to PLN 120,000 annually and 32% on the excess above PLN 120,000. Additionally, a tax-free amount of PLN 30,000 applies. The advantage is the ability to use tax reliefs and joint settlement with a spouse.</p><h2 id="liniowy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Flat tax 19%</h2><p>Flat tax is a fixed rate of 19% on income, regardless of its amount. There are no tax thresholds or tax-free amounts. The health contribution for flat tax is 4.9% of income, which is significantly less than 9% under the tax scale. It pays off at incomes above PLN 100,000-120,000 per year.</p><h2 id="ryczalt" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Lump-sum tax on recorded revenues</h2><p>Lump-sum tax is calculated on revenue (not income), meaning no deduction of business costs. Rates depend on the type of activity: 8.5% (most services), 12% (IT services, rental), 15% (consulting, brokerage), and 17% (liberal professions). It is particularly attractive for entrepreneurs with low operating costs.</p><h2 id="porownanie" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Comparison — when does what pay off</h2><p>Key decision factors are: cost level (high = scale or flat, low = lump sum), income level (low = scale, high = flat or lump sum), ability to use reliefs (many reliefs = scale), and type of activity (determines lump-sum rate). It is worth conducting an individual simulation or consulting a tax advisor.</p><h2 id="terminy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Deadlines for changing tax form</h2><p>Changing the taxation form for a given tax year is possible by the 20th day of the month following the month in which the first revenue was earned. In practice, for most entrepreneurs this means a deadline of February 20. The change is reported through a CEIDG update or a statement to the head of the tax office.</p>` },
  { file: 'ksef-faktury-papierowe-2026.html', title: 'KSeF and Paper Invoices — Changes from 2026', desc: 'National e-Invoice System (KSeF) vs paper invoices — who is affected, implementation timeline, and how to prepare for changes from 2026.', badge: 'KSeF', badgeColor: '#f39c12', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 12.12.2025', toc: [['#czym-jest-ksef','What is KSeF?'],['#harmonogram','Implementation timeline'],['#kogo-dotyczy','Who is affected?'],['#faktury-papierowe','What about paper invoices?'],['#przygotowanie','How to prepare'],['#korzysci','Benefits of KSeF']], content: `<h2 id="czym-jest-ksef" class="fw-bold mb-3">What is KSeF?</h2><p>The National e-Invoice System (KSeF) is a central IT system run by the Ministry of Finance for issuing, receiving, and storing structured invoices. A structured invoice is an invoice in XML format compliant with the FA(2) schema, which is sent to KSeF and stored in the system for 10 years.</p><p>KSeF works as a central repository — each invoice issued in the system receives a unique identification number (KSeF number) and is immediately available to both parties: the issuer and the recipient.</p><h2 id="harmonogram" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Implementation timeline</h2><p>The obligation to use KSeF is being introduced in stages. From February 1, 2026, the obligation to issue structured invoices applies to active VAT taxpayers whose sales value exceeded PLN 200 million in the previous year. From April 1, 2026, the obligation is extended to all active VAT taxpayers, regardless of turnover.</p><h2 id="kogo-dotyczy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Who is affected?</h2><p>The KSeF obligation primarily applies to active VAT taxpayers issuing invoices in domestic B2B transactions. This means every invoice issued to another entrepreneur must go through the KSeF system. For entrepreneurs using a business incubator, the KSeF obligation rests on the incubator as the invoice-issuing entity.</p><h2 id="faktury-papierowe" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">What about paper invoices?</h2><p>Implementing mandatory KSeF does not mean a complete ban on paper invoices. An invoice issued in KSeF can be shared with a contractor as a visualization — printout or PDF file. However, such visualization must contain the KSeF number. Paper invoices without a KSeF number will lose legal validity in B2B transactions.</p><h2 id="przygotowanie" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to prepare</h2><p>Preparation for KSeF requires actions on several levels. First, the entrepreneur must obtain an authorization token for logging into the system. Second, the invoicing system must be adapted to generate invoices in XML format. Third, it is worth testing invoice issuance in the test environment before the obligation takes effect.</p><h2 id="korzysci" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Benefits of KSeF</h2><p>Despite initial implementation difficulties, KSeF brings several benefits: automation of accounting processes (20-30% time savings), shortened VAT refund period (40 days instead of 60), and elimination of fake invoices. For FDK incubator clients, KSeF handling is done automatically — no additional actions are needed.</p>` },
  { file: 'najnizsza-krajowa-2026.html', title: 'What Is the Minimum Wage and Total Employee Cost in 2026?', desc: 'Minimum wage in 2026 is PLN 4,806 gross. Check the total cost of employing a worker, employer ZUS contributions, and comparison with previous years.', badge: 'Employment', badgeColor: '#e74c3c', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 09.12.2025', toc: [['#minimalna','Minimum gross wage from January 2026'],['#skladki','Employer-side ZUS contributions'],['#calkowity-koszt','Total cost of employing a worker'],['#porownanie','Comparison with previous years'],['#konsekwencje','Consequences of the increase for entrepreneurs']], content: `<h2 id="minimalna" class="fw-bold mb-3">Minimum gross wage from January 2026</h2><p>From January 1, 2026, the minimum wage in Poland is PLN 4,666 gross per month. This is an increase of PLN 366 compared to July 2025 (PLN 4,300). The government decided on a one-time increase, abandoning the model of two increases per year.</p><p>The hourly rate for civil-law contracts increases to PLN 30.50 gross. The minimum wage serves as a reference point for many other benefits and fees.</p><h2 id="skladki" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Employer-side ZUS contributions</h2><p>An employer hiring a worker on a minimum-wage employment contract must pay additional contributions that significantly increase the actual employment cost. The employer's pension contribution is 9.76%, disability — 6.50%, accident — approx. 1.67%, Labor Fund — 2.45%, and FGSP — 0.10%. Total employer burden is approximately 20.48% of gross wages.</p><h2 id="calkowity-koszt" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Total cost of employing a worker</h2><p>At a minimum gross wage of PLN 4,666, the total cost of employing a worker on an employment contract is approximately PLN 5,621 per month. Annually, this gives over PLN 67,450 per full-time minimum-wage employee.</p><h2 id="porownanie" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Comparison with previous years</h2><p>The dynamics of minimum wage growth in Poland in recent years is impressive. In just three years (2023-2026), the minimum wage increased by over PLN 1,170 gross, representing a nearly 34% increase. This places Poland among the EU leaders in minimum wage growth rate.</p><h2 id="konsekwencje" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Consequences of the increase for entrepreneurs</h2><p>The minimum wage increase affects not only employment costs but also other entrepreneur obligations. The minimum ZUS contribution base increases for self-employed persons, as does the minimum hourly rate on civil-law contracts. For micro-entrepreneurs and freelancers, cooperation within a business incubator may be an alternative that allows cost optimization.</p>` },
  { file: 'zasilek-dla-bezrobotnych-2026.html', title: 'Who Can Receive Unemployment Benefits in 2026?', desc: 'Conditions for receiving unemployment benefits in 2026. Check who qualifies, what amounts apply, and how to file at the labor office.', badge: 'Employment', badgeColor: '#e74c3c', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 04.12.2025', toc: [['#warunki','Conditions for obtaining unemployed status'],['#kwalifikacja','Who qualifies for benefits'],['#kwoty','Benefit amounts in 2026'],['#wniosek','How to file at the labor office'],['#utrata','When you lose the right to benefits']], content: `<h2 id="warunki" class="fw-bold mb-3">Conditions for obtaining unemployed status</h2><p>To obtain unemployed status in 2026, you must register at the district labor office appropriate for your permanent or temporary residence. Registration can be done in person or online via the praca.gov.pl portal using a trusted profile or qualified signature.</p><p>The person applying for unemployed status must meet several conditions — they cannot be employed or performing other paid work, must be able and ready to take up employment full-time, and cannot receive a pension or other benefits excluding registration.</p><h2 id="kwalifikacja" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Who qualifies for benefits</h2><p>The right to unemployment benefits is granted to a person who in the 18 months preceding registration worked a total of at least 365 days earning at least the minimum wage. This period includes both employment contracts and civil-law contracts with paid contributions.</p><p>People who were dismissed by the employer receive benefits from the date of registration. Those who resigned themselves must wait 90 days before benefit payments begin.</p><h2 id="kwoty" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Benefit amounts in 2026</h2><p>The unemployment benefit amount in 2026 depends on work seniority. The basic benefit (100%) for people with 5-20 years of seniority is PLN 1,491.90 gross for the first three months, then PLN 1,171.60 gross. People with less than 5 years receive 80%, those with over 20 years receive 120%.</p><h2 id="wniosek" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to file at the labor office</h2><p>Registration requires an ID card, employment certificates from previous jobs, diplomas, and for former business owners — a certificate of deletion from CEIDG. The simplest form is electronic pre-registration via praca.gov.pl, after which the office schedules a personal visit for document verification.</p><h2 id="utrata" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">When you lose the right to benefits</h2><p>The right to benefits expires automatically after the benefit period (6 or 12 months). Earlier loss occurs upon taking employment, starting a business, or refusing a suitable job offer without justification. Engaging in unregistered activity or incubator cooperation does not automatically exclude benefit rights, provided income does not exceed half the minimum wage monthly.</p>` },
  { file: 'dzialalnosc-nierejestrowana-2026.html', title: 'What Changes Apply to Unregistered Activity in 2026?', desc: 'New limits and rules for unregistered activity in 2026. Check changes in revenue thresholds, KSeF obligations, and how to legally operate without registration.', badge: 'Incubator', badgeColor: '#7c5cbf', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 01.12.2025', toc: [['#czym-jest','What is unregistered activity'],['#nowe-limity','New revenue limits in 2026'],['#ksef','KSeF-related obligations'],['#podatki','Tax settlements and records'],['#alternatywy','Alternatives — business incubator']], content: `<h2 id="czym-jest" class="fw-bold mb-3">What is unregistered activity</h2><p>Unregistered activity is a form of earning introduced in 2018 by the Entrepreneurs' Law Act. It allows individuals to conduct small-scale business without the need to register in CEIDG, pay ZUS contributions, or maintain full accounting.</p><p>This form can be used by individuals who have not operated a registered business in any of the last 60 months. It is ideal for people testing a business idea, earning occasionally, or providing small services.</p><h2 id="nowe-limity" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">New revenue limits in 2026</h2><p>From January 1, 2026, the revenue limit for unregistered activity is 75% of the minimum wage. At a minimum wage of PLN 4,666 gross, this gives a monthly revenue limit of PLN 3,499.50. Exceeding this threshold in any month means an obligation to register a business in CEIDG within 7 days.</p><p>The limit applies to revenue, not income — meaning the total amount of inflows without deducting costs. The change from 50% to 75% of the minimum wage, introduced in 2024, gave greater flexibility.</p><h2 id="ksef" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">KSeF-related obligations</h2><p>In 2026, people conducting unregistered activity are generally exempt from the obligation to issue structured invoices in KSeF, as they are not active VAT taxpayers. They can still issue receipts or simplified invoices in paper or electronic form.</p><h2 id="podatki" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Tax settlements and records</h2><p>Income from unregistered activity is settled in the annual PIT-36 return as income from other sources. It is taxed according to the tax scale — 12% up to PLN 120,000 combined income, and 32% above. The tax-free amount of PLN 30,000 also applies. The obligation is to keep simplified sales records.</p><h2 id="alternatywy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Alternatives — business incubator</h2><p>For people whose unregistered activity limit is insufficient but who don't want to start their own company yet, a business incubator is an excellent alternative. The FDK incubator offers invoicing without revenue limits, accounting and tax support, and business consulting. The effective tax rate can be as low as 6%. Transitioning from unregistered activity to an incubator is smooth and requires no complex formalities.</p>` },
  { file: 'optymalizacja-podatkowa-2026.html', title: 'How Is Tax Optimization Changing in 2026?', desc: 'Tax system changes in 2026. New optimization rules, who gains, who loses, and how to legally reduce taxes.', badge: 'Taxes', badgeColor: '#2ecc71', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 24.11.2025', toc: [['#przeglad','Overview of tax changes in 2026'],['#skala','Tax scale and tax-free amount'],['#ryczalt','Lump sum and flat tax — what changes'],['#zyskuja','Who benefits from new regulations'],['#strategie','Legal tax optimization strategies']], content: `<h2 id="przeglad" class="fw-bold mb-3">Overview of tax changes in 2026</h2><p>2026 brings further modifications to the Polish tax system that directly affect opportunities for fiscal burden optimization. The most important changes concern indexation of tax thresholds, modification of cost-of-revenue deduction rules, and tightening of the anti-avoidance clause.</p><p>The Ministry of Finance continues the trend of digitalizing tax settlements. Mandatory e-invoices in KSeF, automatic exchange of tax information between EU countries, and expansion of the National Revenue Administration analytical system mean that the space for aggressive tax optimization is significantly narrowing.</p><h2 id="skala" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Tax scale and tax-free amount</h2><p>The tax-free amount in 2026 remains at PLN 30,000. The first tax threshold (12%) applies up to PLN 120,000 income, above which the rate increases to 32%. The health contribution for entrepreneurs on the tax scale is 9% of income and is not deductible from tax.</p><h2 id="ryczalt" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Lump sum and flat tax — what changes</h2><p>Flat tax at 19% remains an attractive option for entrepreneurs with income above PLN 120,000 annually. The health contribution for flat tax is 4.9% of income. Lump-sum rates remain unchanged — from 2% to 17% depending on the type of activity. A novelty in 2026 is the tightening of rules for qualifying revenues to specific lump-sum rates.</p><h2 id="zyskuja" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Who benefits from new regulations</h2><p>The biggest beneficiaries are people with low and medium incomes — the tax-free amount of PLN 30,000 and the first threshold of PLN 120,000 protect them from excessive taxation. Families with children also benefit from unchanged family tax reliefs. Those who lose are high-income sole proprietors — rising ZUS contributions, KSeF obligations, and tightening of the anti-avoidance clause limit optimization possibilities.</p><h2 id="strategie" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Legal tax optimization strategies</h2><p>The most effective legal tax optimization strategy in 2026 is choosing the right form of taxation and business operation. For freelancers with revenues up to PLN 200,000 annually, cooperation with a business incubator allows effective taxation at just 6%. Other legal methods include: maximizing available reliefs (R&D, IP Box for software creators), proper deduction of business costs, and using depreciation programs. The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation offers free consultations on choosing the optimal form of business operation.</p>` },
  { file: 'najnizsza-krajowa-na-reke-2026.html', title: 'How Will the Minimum Wage Change in 2026 and How Much Will You Actually Take Home?', desc: 'Detailed analysis of net minimum wage in 2026. How much remains after deducting ZUS contributions and income tax.', badge: 'Employment', badgeColor: '#e74c3c', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 21.11.2025', toc: [['#brutto-netto','From gross to net — step by step'],['#skladki-pracownika','ZUS contributions deducted from salary'],['#podatek','Income tax advance'],['#na-reke','How much remains take-home in 2026'],['#porady','How to increase your net salary']], content: `<h2 id="brutto-netto" class="fw-bold mb-3">From gross to net — step by step</h2><p>Gross salary is the amount in the employment contract, from which the employer deducts social insurance contributions, health contribution, and income tax advance. The difference between gross and all deductions gives the net salary — the amount the employee actually receives.</p><p>At the minimum wage of PLN 4,666 gross in 2026, the calculation process includes several stages: first social insurance contributions are deducted, then the health contribution is calculated from the reduced base, and finally the income tax advance is calculated.</p><h2 id="skladki-pracownika" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">ZUS contributions deducted from salary</h2><p>From the gross salary of PLN 4,666, the employee pays three social insurance contributions: pension 9.76% (PLN 455.40), disability 1.50% (PLN 69.99), and sickness 2.45% (PLN 114.32). Total social contributions are PLN 639.71. The health contribution is 9% of the reduced base, i.e., PLN 362.37.</p><h2 id="podatek" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Income tax advance</h2><p>The tax base is gross salary minus social contributions and tax-deductible costs (PLN 250 monthly standard). At standard costs, the tax base is PLN 3,776. Tax at 12% is PLN 453.12, minus the tax-reducing amount of PLN 300, giving an advance of PLN 153.</p><h2 id="na-reke" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How much remains take-home in 2026</h2><p>After deducting all contributions and the tax advance, a minimum-wage worker receives approximately PLN 3,510.92 net. For comparison, in 2025 (from July) at PLN 4,300 gross, the net amount was approximately PLN 3,261.53. People under 26 using the youth relief do not pay income tax and receive approximately PLN 3,663.92.</p><h2 id="porady" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to increase your net salary</h2><p>There are several legal ways to increase the net amount: submit the PIT-2 statement to the employer, declare higher tax-deductible costs for commuters, and use available tax reliefs. For people seeking alternative forms of earning, cooperation within a business incubator allows for significantly higher tax efficiency. The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation will help choose the most advantageous solution.</p>` },
  { file: 'odwieszenie-dzialalnosci-2025.html', title: 'When Is It Worth Resuming Your Business and How to Do It?', desc: 'Practical guide to resuming a suspended business. Step-by-step procedure, deadlines, and obligations toward ZUS and the tax office.', badge: 'Guide', badgeColor: '#3498db', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 12.11.2025', toc: [['#kiedy-warto','When to resume your business'],['#procedura','Resumption procedure step by step'],['#zus','ZUS obligations after resumption'],['#podatki','Tax settlements after resumption'],['#alternatywy','Alternatives — incubator instead of resumption']], content: `<h2 id="kiedy-warto" class="fw-bold mb-3">When to resume your business</h2><p>Suspending a business is a popular solution for entrepreneurs who temporarily generate no revenue. However, the decision to resume requires careful thought. It is worth doing when new orders or contracts appear, the market situation changes favorably, or the period during which suspension was beneficial ends.</p><p>Remember that business suspension can last indefinitely — there is no longer a requirement to resume after 24 months. However, too long a suspension may raise doubts among contractors and financial institutions when assessing credibility.</p><h2 id="procedura" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Resumption procedure step by step</h2><p>Resuming a business requires submitting a CEIDG-1 application with the resumption field checked. The application can be submitted electronically through biznes.gov.pl, in person at the commune office, or by registered mail. The resumption date must be specified — it can be a future or current date, but not retroactive.</p><p>After submission, CEIDG automatically notifies ZUS, the tax office, and GUS. The process is free and usually takes 1 business day.</p><h2 id="zus" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">ZUS obligations after resumption</h2><p>From the day of resumption, the entrepreneur is again subject to mandatory social and health insurance. ZUS automatically restores the registration. If the entrepreneur was using the startup relief or preferential contributions before suspension, the unused period "unfreezes" and can be continued.</p><p>The first ZUS contribution after resumption must be paid by the 20th of the month following the resumption month. If resumption occurred mid-month, contributions are calculated proportionally.</p><h2 id="podatki" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Tax settlements after resumption</h2><p>After resumption, the taxation form remains the same as before suspension — unless the entrepreneur submits a change request by the 20th of the month following resumption. The entrepreneur must resume keeping the Revenue and Expense Book (KPiR) or revenue records from the day of resumption.</p><h2 id="alternatywy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Alternatives — incubator instead of resumption</h2><p>If you plan to resume earning activity but fear the fixed costs of running your own business (especially ZUS contributions), consider a business incubator as an alternative. Within the FDK incubator, you don't pay ZUS, don't have to keep accounts, and the effective tax rate is just 6%. This solution is particularly beneficial for people unsure whether their business will generate stable revenues. The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation offers support at every stage.</p>` },
  { file: 'l4-umowa-zlecenie-2025.html', title: 'When Does a Civil-Law Contract Entitle You to Sick Leave (L4)?', desc: 'Right to sick leave L4 on a civil-law contract. When can a contractor receive sickness benefits and how to prepare for it.', badge: 'Employment', badgeColor: '#e74c3c', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 07.11.2025', toc: [['#warunki','Conditions for receiving L4'],['#skladka-chorobowa','Voluntary sickness contribution'],['#okres-wyczekiwania','Waiting period'],['#wysokosc','Benefit amounts'],['#praktyczne','Practical tips']], content: `<h2 id="warunki" class="fw-bold mb-3">Conditions for receiving L4</h2><p>A person working under a civil-law contract (umowa zlecenie) can receive a sick leave benefit (L4) only if they are covered by voluntary sickness insurance. Unlike employment contracts, where sickness insurance is mandatory, on civil-law contracts it is the contractor's choice to opt in.</p><p>To be covered by sickness insurance, the contractor must submit a declaration (ZUS ZUA) through the principal, indicating their willingness to pay the voluntary sickness contribution. Coverage begins from the day indicated in the declaration.</p><h2 id="skladka-chorobowa" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Voluntary sickness contribution</h2><p>The sickness contribution is 2.45% of the declared contribution base. For people on civil-law contracts, the base is typically the actual remuneration from the contract. The contribution is deducted from the contractor's remuneration by the principal and transferred to ZUS along with other contributions.</p><h2 id="okres-wyczekiwania" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Waiting period</h2><p>The right to sickness benefit does not arise immediately upon joining voluntary sickness insurance. There is a 90-day waiting period (continuous coverage) before the contractor becomes eligible for benefits. During this period, even if the person gets sick, they will not receive the benefit.</p><h2 id="wysokosc" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Benefit amounts</h2><p>The sickness benefit for people on civil-law contracts is 80% of the average monthly remuneration from the last 12 months (or the period of coverage if shorter). For hospitalization, the rate is 70%. The benefit is paid by ZUS from the first day of illness.</p><h2 id="praktyczne" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Practical tips</h2><p>If you work on civil-law contracts and want sick leave protection, opt into sickness insurance as early as possible to complete the 90-day waiting period. Keep in mind that if you have a gap in coverage (even one day), the waiting period resets. For people seeking more comprehensive protection, working through a business incubator may offer better terms, as the incubator handles all insurance formalities.</p>` },
  { file: 'podpis-epuap-2025.html', title: 'How to Effectively Sign a Document on ePUAP?', desc: 'Step-by-step instructions for signing documents on ePUAP. Trusted profile, qualified signature, and most common problems with electronic signatures.', badge: 'Guide', badgeColor: '#3498db', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 04.11.2025', toc: [['#co-to-epuap','What is ePUAP?'],['#profil-zaufany','Trusted profile'],['#podpis-kwalifikowany','Qualified electronic signature'],['#krok-po-kroku','Signing step by step'],['#problemy','Most common problems and solutions']], content: `<h2 id="co-to-epuap" class="fw-bold mb-3">What is ePUAP?</h2><p>ePUAP (Electronic Platform of Public Administration Services) is an internet platform that enables citizens and entrepreneurs to handle official matters electronically. Through ePUAP, you can submit applications, declarations, and other documents to public offices without leaving home.</p><p>A key element of ePUAP is the ability to sign documents electronically, which gives them the same legal force as a traditional handwritten signature. This is essential for business registration, submitting tax returns, and communicating with government offices.</p><h2 id="profil-zaufany" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Trusted profile</h2><p>A trusted profile (profil zaufany) is the most popular method of electronic identification in Poland. It can be set up for free through online banking, at a confirmation point (e.g., post office, tax office), or using an e-ID card. The profile is valid for 3 years and must be renewed after expiration.</p><p>For foreigners with a PESEL number, setting up a trusted profile is possible through banking systems that support this function (most major banks in Poland offer this). Without a PESEL, confirmation must be done in person at a designated point.</p><h2 id="podpis-kwalifikowany" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Qualified electronic signature</h2><p>A qualified electronic signature is a more advanced form of electronic identification, providing the highest level of legal certainty. Unlike a trusted profile, it requires purchasing a certificate from a qualified provider (e.g., Certum, Szafir) and a physical device (USB token or smart card).</p><h2 id="krok-po-kroku" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Signing step by step</h2><p>To sign a document on ePUAP: 1) Log into the epuap.gov.pl platform, 2) Find the appropriate service or upload your document, 3) Fill in the required fields, 4) Click "Sign and send," 5) Choose your signing method (trusted profile or qualified signature), 6) Confirm with an authorization code (sent via SMS for trusted profile). The signed document is sent to the recipient and stored in your account.</p><h2 id="problemy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Most common problems and solutions</h2><p>Common issues include: expired trusted profile (renew at gov.pl), wrong browser (use Chrome or Firefox), disabled JavaScript or pop-up blockers, expired authorization code (request a new one), and documents too large (maximum 5 MB per attachment). If problems persist, contact the ePUAP helpline or visit a confirmation point in person. The Firma Dla Każdego Foundation team can assist with ePUAP-related procedures.</p>` },
  { file: 'wakacje-skladkowe-zus-2025.html', title: 'How Does the "ZUS Contribution Holiday" Relief Work?', desc: 'ZUS Contribution Holiday — new relief for micro-entrepreneurs. Who can use it, how to apply, and how much you can save on ZUS contributions.', badge: 'ZUS', badgeColor: '#2ecc71', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 30.10.2025', toc: [['#czym-jest','What is the ZUS Contribution Holiday?'],['#kto-moze','Who can use it?'],['#warunki','Conditions and limitations'],['#wniosek','How to apply'],['#oszczednosci','How much can you save?']], content: `<h2 id="czym-jest" class="fw-bold mb-3">What is the ZUS Contribution Holiday?</h2><p>The ZUS Contribution Holiday (wakacje skladkowe) is a new relief introduced in late 2024, allowing micro-entrepreneurs to be exempt from paying social insurance contributions for one selected month per year. During this month, the entrepreneur does not pay pension, disability, accident, or sickness contributions — they are covered by the state budget.</p><p>The relief aims to reduce the financial burden on the smallest businesses, giving them a month of "breathing room" from mandatory ZUS payments. The health contribution must still be paid during the holiday month.</p><h2 id="kto-moze" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Who can use it?</h2><p>The relief is available to entrepreneurs who: are registered in CEIDG (sole proprietors), employ a maximum of 9 people (micro-enterprise definition), were registered as contribution payers for at least 6 months before applying, and were not in a suspension period in the month preceding the application month.</p><h2 id="warunki" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Conditions and limitations</h2><p>The contribution holiday can be used once per calendar year for one chosen month. The entrepreneur must submit the application at least one month before the intended holiday month. During the holiday month, the entrepreneur can continue running their business normally — there are no restrictions on earning revenue.</p><p>Income limits also apply — the entrepreneur's income in the previous year cannot exceed the equivalent of 10 times the minimum wage on January 1 of the holiday year.</p><h2 id="wniosek" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How to apply</h2><p>The application is submitted electronically through the PUE ZUS (e-ZUS) platform at least one month before the chosen holiday month. The application form is called RWS. ZUS processes the application within 40 days and informs the entrepreneur of the decision. If approved, contributions for the selected month are covered by the state budget.</p><h2 id="oszczednosci" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">How much can you save?</h2><p>At full ZUS in 2025/2026 (approximately PLN 1,600/month), the monthly savings from the contribution holiday amount to about PLN 1,200-1,400 (social contributions without health). Over a year, this is a one-month relief that can be strategically timed to a low-revenue month. For entrepreneurs seeking greater contribution savings throughout the year, a business incubator remains a more comprehensive solution — with monthly costs of just PLN 400 and no separate ZUS obligation.</p>` },
  { file: 'ubezpieczenie-zdrowotne-bez-pracy-2025.html', title: 'How to Get Health Insurance Without a Job?', desc: 'Ways to obtain health insurance without employment. Registration at the labor office, reporting through a family member, KRUS, and other options.', badge: 'ZUS', badgeColor: '#2ecc71', author: 'FDK Team &middot; 22.10.2025', toc: [['#sposoby','Ways to get health insurance'],['#urzad-pracy','Registration at the labor office'],['#czlonek-rodziny','Reporting through a family member'],['#inne-opcje','Other options'],['#cudzoziemcy','Options for foreigners']], content: `<h2 id="sposoby" class="fw-bold mb-3">Ways to get health insurance</h2><p>In Poland, access to public healthcare (NFZ) requires being covered by health insurance. People who are not employed, not running a business, and not covered by other insurance titles face a gap in coverage. Fortunately, there are several legal ways to obtain health insurance without formal employment.</p><p>The most common options include: registering at the labor office as unemployed, being reported as a family member by an insured person, voluntary health insurance, student insurance, and working through a business incubator.</p><h2 id="urzad-pracy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Registration at the labor office</h2><p>The simplest way to obtain health insurance without a job is to register as unemployed at the district labor office. Upon registration, the person is automatically covered by health insurance funded by the state budget. This coverage extends to the registered person and their family members (spouse, children).</p><p>Registration requires an ID card, employment certificates, and diplomas. The process can be started online at praca.gov.pl. Being registered as unemployed comes with obligations — you must report to the office on scheduled dates and accept suitable job offers.</p><h2 id="czlonek-rodziny" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Reporting through a family member</h2><p>If your spouse, parent, or another family member is covered by health insurance (e.g., through employment), they can report you as a family member for health insurance purposes. This is done through the employer of the insured family member using the ZUS ZCNA form. Coverage is free and gives full access to NFZ services.</p><h2 id="inne-opcje" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Other options</h2><p>Voluntary health insurance is available for people who don't qualify for other forms of coverage. The monthly cost is approximately 9% of the average wage (about PLN 700 in 2025). Students up to age 26 are covered by their parents' insurance; those over 26 are covered by the university. Farmers can be insured through KRUS.</p><h2 id="cudzoziemcy" class="fw-bold mb-3 mt-5">Options for foreigners</h2><p>Foreigners legally residing in Poland have access to the same options as Polish citizens. Registration at the labor office is available to foreigners with work authorization. Family reporting works for foreign family members of insured persons. Working through the Firma Dla Każdego business incubator automatically provides health insurance coverage, as contributions are paid by the incubator on behalf of the participant.</p>` }
];

